Using 2.0.0.BUILD-SNAPSHOT and the health endpoint of spring-boot-actuator for solr queries a URL of `/solr/admin/ping` when it should use `/solr/<corename>/admin/ping`. This results in a 404 error and a "down" status, even though solr is actually running fine. This was tested with solr 6.3.0

This may be related to https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATASOLR-364 but it would be nice for it to be enhanced for multi-core cases anyway. One way this could be done is below, using a `SolrClientFactory` instead of a `SolrClient` and then iterating over all the cores that have been registered:

```
package org.springframework.boot.actuate.health;

import org.apache.solr.client.solrj.SolrClient;
import org.springframework.data.solr.server.SolrClientFactory;

public class SolrHealthIndicator extends AbstractHealthIndicator {

	private final SolrClientFactory solrClientFactory;

	public SolrHealthIndicator(SolrClientFactory solrClientFactory) {
		this.solrClientFactory = solrClientFactory;
	}

	@Override
	protected void doHealthCheck(Health.Builder builder) throws Exception {
		for (String core : this.solrClientFactory.getCores()) {
			SolrClient client = this.solrClientFactory.getSolrClient(core);
			Object status = client.ping().getResponse().get("status");
			builder.withDetail(core, status);
		}
                builder.up();
	}
}
```

After upgrading to Spring Boot 1.5.1 my application fails to start claiming that a bean cannot be found.
The bean in question is a simple class named `Validator`, marked as `@Component`.

MWE demonstrating the issue:
```java
package com.example;

import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;

@SpringBootApplication
public class ValdemoApplication {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(ValdemoApplication.class, args);
    }
}

@Component
class Validator {
}

@Component
class Foo {

    @Autowired
    private Validator validator;

}
```

The code shown will run fine on Spring Boot 1.4.3, but will fail to start on 1.5.1.
```
***************************
APPLICATION FAILED TO START
***************************

Description:

Field validator in com.example.Foo required a bean of type 'com.example.Validator' that could not be found.
```

I'm using Spring Boot 1.5.2.  

I have a `JsonApiMessageConverter` that I am trying to add to the `messageConverter` list.  I'm trying to follow the documentation at http://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/current/reference/htmlsingle/#boot-features-spring-mvc-message-converters.

I have this config object:

```
@Configuration
public class MessageConverterConfig {

    @Autowired
    JsonApiMessageConverter jsonApiMessageConverter;

    @Bean
    public HttpMessageConverters customConverters() {
        return new HttpMessageConverters(false, Arrays.asList(jsonApiMessageConverter, new StringHttpMessageConverter()));
    }

}
```

I can set a break point in `customConverters` and see that its getting called.  However, another break point in `AbstractMessageConverterMethodProcessor` at line 224 shows that `this.messageConverters` does not contain my custom converters, so the default Jackson converter is used instead.

If I extend `WebMvcConfigurerAdapter` I can use `configureMessageConverters` or `extendMessageConverters` to add my custom converters without a problem.
